    <section id="blog-details">
        <div class="blog-container">
            <h2 class="section-title">The Sunset Faded to Twilight</h2>
            <img src="~/assets/images/common/a1.jpg" alt="Man thinking"
                 style="width: 100%; max-height: 400px; object-fit: cover; border-radius: 10px" />
            <p class="date" style="color: #E4CCB4;">April 25, 2025 - TASTE LIFE</p>
            <p style="color: #ccc; margin-top: 20px; line-height: 1.6">
                I began walking, directionless, in the warm
                evening breeze. The colors faded slowly, and the quiet streets echoed with the soft hum of espresso
                machines and the gentle murmur of distant conversations drifting from open cafés.
            </p>
            <p>
                My heart, untamed and full of courage and curiosity, beat in rhythm with the cobblestones beneath my
                feet, each step a whisper of exploration. The twilight in Italy, golden and unhurried, wrapped
                itself around every corner of the city, painting balconies, lanterns, and ivy-covered walls with a
                glow that made time feel suspended.
            </p>
            <p>
                The smell of freshly ground coffee drifted through the alleys, like an old friend welcoming me home.
                I followed it, not with purpose, but with instinct — led by senses rather than destination. The air
                was filled with a quiet kind of magic; laughter from a small table in the corner of a café, the
                clink of porcelain cups, the low hum of a song playing from inside.
            </p>
            <p>
                I paused before a little coffee shop tucked between two ivy-covered buildings. It had no sign, just
                the flickering of a warm light and the comforting sound of milk frothing behind the counter. An old
                man stood inside, humming as he wiped a glass — he nodded at me with the kind of familiarity only
                found in places that make you feel like you’ve been there before, even if it’s your first time.
            </p>
            <p>
                I stepped in, ordered a small espresso, and sat by the window. Outside, the sun had disappeared
                completely, but inside, the warmth remained. It wasn’t just the heat of the coffee — it was the
                feeling of belonging. Of finding something beautiful without searching. Of being exactly where you
                were meant to be.
            </p>
            <p>
                And in that moment, surrounded by strangers and silence, I realized: sometimes, the best journeys
                begin with no map at all — only the smell of coffee, the golden light of twilight, and the heart
                that dares to wander.
            </p>
            <a asp-controller="Blog" asp-action="Index"
               style="display: inline-block; margin-top: 20px; color: #C9A581; text-decoration: none">
                &larr; Back
                to Stories
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>
